<tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="7" class="text-nowrap">3.1 Readable</th>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.1.1 Language of Page</td>
    <td>A</td>
    <td>
        Both assistive technologies and conventional user agents can render text more accurately 
        when the language of the Web page is identified. Screen readers can load the correct pronunciation rules. 
        Visual browsers can display characters and scripts (the writing system) correctly. Media players can show captions correctly. 
        As a result, users with disabilities will be better able to understand the content.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/language-of-page.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.1.1: Language of Page
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Use the lang attribute for the HTML element.
        <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Global_attributes/lang" target="_blank">MDN: lang attributes format (parts)</a>
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.1.2 Language of Parts</td>
    <td>AA</td>
    <td>
        The intent of this Success Criterion is to ensure that user agents can correctly present content written in multiple languages.
        This is especially important when switching between languages that read from left to right and languages that read from right to left, 
        or when text is rendered in a language that uses a different alphabet.
        If there is doubt whether a change in language is intended, consider whether the word would be pronounced the 
        same (except for accent or intonation) in the language of the immediately surrounding text.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/language-of-parts.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.1.2: Language of Parts
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Use the lang attribute for the HTML element.
        And for tags where a switch of language is used.
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.1.3 Unusual Words</td>
    <td>AAA</td>
    <td>
        Certain disabilities make it difficult to understand some words or words used in an  unusual way.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/unusual-words.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.1.3: Unusual Words
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Link to a description list that explains words.
        <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/dl" target="_blank">MDN: The Description List element</a>
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.1.4 Abbreviations</td>
    <td>AAA</td>
    <td>
        The intent of this Success Criterion is to ensure that users can access the expanded form of abbreviations.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/abbreviations.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.1.4: Abbreviations
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Make expanded form of an abbreviation available by associating the expanded form (for example put it in parentheses) with its abbreviation the first time it occurs within a Web page.
        <br>
        Or use the abbr element (<a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/abbr" target="_blank">MDN: The Abbreviation element</a>)
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.1.5 Reading Level</td>
    <td>AAA</td>
    <td>
        Content should be written as clearly and simply as possible.
        Supplemental content is required when text demands reading ability more advanced than the lower secondary education level (more than nine years of school).
        Education levels are defined according to the International Standard Classification of Education [[UNESCO]], which was created to allow international comparison among systems of education.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/reading-level.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.1.5: Reading Level
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Simplify all text or provide a text summary (a h tag that says summary and p tags with the text (simpler language and avarage 16 words sentences)).
        Titles that refer to the name of documents, books, movies, etc are excempt.
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.1.6: Pronunciation</td>
    <td>AAA</td>
    <td>
        The intent of this Success Criterion is to help people who are blind, people who have low vision, and people with reading disabilities to understand content in cases where meaning depends on pronunciation.
        For example, in the English language heteronyms are words that are spelled the same but have different pronunciations and meanings, such as the words desert (abandon) and desert (arid region). 
        If the proper pronunciation can be determined from the context of the sentence, then nothing is required. If it cannot then some mechanism for determining the proper pronunciation would be required.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Cognitive impaired, Visually impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/pronunciation.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.1.6: Pronunciation
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Use the ruby element (HTML 5).
        <br>
        Provide sound files of the pronunciation.
    </td>
</tr>

<tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="6" class="text-nowrap">3.2 Predictable</th>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.2.1: On Focus</td>
    <td>A</td>
    <td>
        Any component that is able to trigger an event when it receives focus must not change the context.
        For example: When a field receives focus, a help dialog window describing the field and providing options opens. 
        As a keyboard user tabs through the Web page, the dialog opens, moving the keyboard focus away from the control 
        every time the user attempts to tab past the field.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visual impaired, cognitive impaired, motor impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/on-focus.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.2.1: On Focus
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Change of content != change of context (changes of context, by their nature, interrupt the user by taking focus). <br>
        Opening a new window, moving focus to a different component, going to a new page (including anything that would look to a user as if they had moved to a new page) or significantly re-arranging the content of a page are examples of changes of context. <br>
        Tooltip that does not recieve focus is ok (but use a button with click event instead).<br>
        Dont remove focus programmatically.
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.2.2: On Input</td>
    <td>A</td>
    <td>
        The intent of this Success Criterion is to ensure that entering data or selecting a form control has predictable effects.
        Setting a form elements (as opposed to activating a link, or using a submit button to explicitly submit a form) shouldn't change the page context, unless the user is advised ahead of time.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/on-input.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.2.2: On Input
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Rather than changing the window.location or a language of a site when a select element is changed, add a submit button.
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.2.3: Consistent Navigation</td>
    <td>AA</td>
    <td>
         Use of consistent presentation and layout for users who interact with repeated content within a set of Web pages and need to locate specific information or functionality more than once.
         It is important to note that the use of the phrase "same order" in this section is not meant to imply that subnavigation menus cannot be used or that blocks of secondary navigation or page structure cannot be used.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/consistent-navigation.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.2.3: Consistent Navigation
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Place menus consistent in the same place. Place searchfields and skip to main content links in the same place.
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.2.4: Consistent Identification</td>
    <td>AA</td>
    <td>
        The intent of this Success Criterion is to ensure consistent identification of functional components that appear repeatedly within a set of Web pages.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/consistent-identification.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.2.4: Consistent Identification
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Keep labels, names, alt text consistent. <br>
        Make sure links to the same resource use the same link text.<br>
        Icons with similar functionality should follow a consistent labeling pattern. For example, "Print x" where x would be the thing to be printed.<br>
        Don't use a search submit button that says "Search" on some pages, and "Find" on others.<br>
        A check mark icon functions as "approved", on one page but as "included" on another. Since they serve different functions, they have different text alternatives. <br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Techniques/html/H2" target="_blank">Also prefer to group link and icon programmatically (and or aria-hidden on link)</a>
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.2.5: Change on Request</td>
    <td>AAA</td>
    <td>
        The intent of this Success Criterion is to encourage design of Web content that gives users full control of changes of context.
        Content that initiates changes of context automatically only when user preferences allow can conform to this Success Criterion.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, motor impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/change-on-request.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.2.5: Change on Request
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        Instead of automatically updating the content, the author provides an "Update now" button that requests a refresh of the content.<br>
        Let the user start a slide show by activating it <br>
        If a link opens in a new window (target blank), write it in the link text.<br>
        Be wary of posting data and render new data when user might not expect it, like when checking a checkbox.
    </td>
</tr>

<tr>
    <th scope="row" rowspan="7" class="text-nowrap">3.3 Input Assistance</th>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.3.1 Error Identification</td>
    <td>A</td>
    <td>
        Users should be made aware that an error has occurred and can determine what is wrong. The error message should be as specific as possible.
        Per the definition in WCAG 2.0, an "input error" is information provided by the user that is not accepted: validation rules, required but omitted.
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: Visually impaired, cognitive impaired</strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/error-identification.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.3.1: Error Identification
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
        It is perfectly acceptable to indicate the error in other ways such as image, color etc, but errors must also be identified using text.<br>
        Identify input that has error programmatically with aria-invalid.
        aria-describedby can be used together with aria-invalid to programmatically connect error messages to the input that has the error.<br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Techniques/aria/ARIA21" target="_blank">ARIA21: Using Aria-Invalid to Indicate An Error Field (Example 2)</a><br>
        Can also place an element with role=alert before the form and put the validation messages there. <br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Techniques/aria/ARIA19" target="_blank">ARIA19: Using ARIA role=alert or Live Regions to Identify Errors</a>
    </td>
</tr>
<tr>
    <td class="text-nowrap">3.3.2 Labels or Instructions</td>
    <td>A</td>
    <td>
        
        <br>
        <strong>It helps: </strong><br>
        <a href="https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/labels-or-instructions.html" target="_blank">
            WCAG: Understanding 3.3.2: Labels or Instructions
        </a>
    </td>
    <td>
